Title : 1947 in British music
Text : {{1940s in music (UK)}}

This is a summary of '''1947 in music''' in the [[United Kingdom]].

==Events==
*[[June 11|11]]–[[15 June]] – The first [[Llangollen International Musical Eisteddfod]] is held in [[Wales]], with [[W. S. Gwynn Williams]] as its musical director.<ref>{{cite web|title=Llangollen International Eisteddfod – How it Started|url=http://www.llangollen.com/eist3.html|publisher=Llangollen International Musical Eisteddfod|accessdate=2012-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824054357/http://www.llangollen.com/eist3.html|archive-date=2017-08-24|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
*[[19 June]] – [[Kathleen Ferrier]] appears at Glyndebourne in Gluck's opera ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]''.
*July – Conductor [[Malcolm Sargent]] is invested with a knighthood for his services to music.<ref>Stone, David. [https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/S/SargentMalcolm.htm "Malcolm Sargent"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006082334/https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/S/SargentMalcolm.htm |date=2014-10-06 }}. ''Who Was Who in the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company'', 13 October 2001, accessed 15 July 2011</ref>
*August – [[Edmund Rubbra]] begins work on his Symphony No. 5 in B flat, Op. 63.<ref>Grover, Ralph Scott. The Music of Edmund Rubbra. Aldershot: Scolar Press: 1993. {{ISBN|0-85967-910-1}}. Includes a worklist.</ref>
*[[22 August]] – The first [[Edinburgh International Festival]] opens.  Its co-founder and first director is Sir [[Rudolf Bing]].  The first Festival concentrates mainly on classical music, a highlight being concerts given by the [[Vienna Philharmonic]], reunited with their erstwhile conductor [[Bruno Walter]], who had left Europe after the [[Anschluss|Nazi occupation of his homeland]].<ref>G Bruce, Festival in the North, The story of the Edinburgh Festival, Robert Hale, London 1975, p.20</ref>
*[[3 November]] – The [[Royal Variety Performance]], held at the [[London Palladium]] and attended by King [[George VI of the United Kingdom|George VI]], includes performances by [[Bud Flanagan]], [[Wilson, Keppel and Betty]], [[Borrah Minnevitch]]'s Harmonica Rascals, Valerie Tandy and [[Gracie Fields]].
*December – [[Benjamin Britten]] and singers [[Joan Cross]] and [[Peter Pears]] combine with designer [[John Piper (artist)|John Piper]] and producer [[Eric Crozier]] to found the [[English Opera Group]].<ref>Gilbert, Susie (2009). ''Opera for Everybody''. London: Faber and Faber. {{ISBN|978-0-571-22493-7}}. p. 107</ref><ref>Mitchell, Donald (ed) (2004). ''Letters From A Life: Selected Letters of Benjamin Britten, Vol. 3 1946–51''. London: Faber and Faber. {{ISBN|0-571-22282-X}}. p. 138</ref>
*''date unknown''
**[[Jack Brymer]] becomes principal clarinettist of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]].
**[[Gracie Fields]] hosts ''Our Gracie's Working Party'' on BBC radio; in the series, she visits twelve towns (beginning with Rochdale), compering and performing in a live show of music and entertainment, with local talents on the bill.

==Popular music==
*[[Anne Shelton (singer)|Anne Shelton]] – "The Night Has A Thousand Eyes"<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/artist/388299-Anne-Shelton Discogs discography]. Accessed 22 June 2014</ref>
*[[Lizbeth Webb]] – "This is My Lovely Day" (by [[Vivian Ellis]], from the musical ''Bless the Bride'')

==Classical music: new works==
*[[Lennox Berkeley]] – Piano Concerto in B flat
*[[Doreen Carwithen]] (Mary Alwyn) – ''ODTAA (One Damn Thing After Another)''
*[[Vivian Ellis]] – ''Coronation Scot''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dw.asp?dc=W4230_GBAJY9686816|title=Coronation Scot|website=Hyperion|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>
*[[Ralph Vaughan Williams]] – Introduction and Fugue for two pianos

==Opera==
*[[Benjamin Britten]] – ''[[Albert Herring]]''

==Film and Incidental music==
*[[Brian Easdale]] – ''[[Black Narcissus]]'', starring [[Deborah Kerr]] and [[David Farrar (actor)|David Farrar]].

==Musical theatre==
*[[7 April]] – ''[[Together Again (musical)|Together Again]]'', a London [[revue]] starring [[The Crazy Gang]], opens at the [[Victoria Palace Theatre]] and runs for 1566 performances.
*[[26 April]] –  ''[[Bless the Bride]]'' (music by [[Vivian Ellis]], book and lyrics by [[A. P. Herbert]]), produced by [[Charles B. Cochran]], opens at the [[Adelphi Theatre]] and runs for 886 performances. It stars [[Georges Guétary]], [[Lizbeth Webb]], [[Anona Winn]] and [[Brian Reece]].
*[[7 June]] – The London production of ''[[Annie Get Your Gun (musical)|Annie Get Your Gun]]'' ([[Irving Berlin]]) opens at the [[London Coliseum|Coliseum]] and runs for 1304 performances.
*[[3 October]] – [[Cicely Courtneidge]] reprises her starring role from the London production of ''[[Under the Counter (musical)|Under the Counter]]'' in a Broadway production at the [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]], but the show closes after only 27 performances.
*[[21 October]] – The [[West End theatre|London]] production of ''[[Finian's Rainbow]]'' ([[Burton Lane]] and [[E.Y. Harburg]]) opens at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]] and runs for 55 performances.

